War Project -- tCHAPTER 14 Beyond the Berlin Myth: The Local, the Global and the IBA 87 -- tPART FOUR Berlin After Unification: Looking Back and Beyond -- tCHAPTER 15 Stereographic City: Berlin Photography in the Wende Era -- tCHAPTER 16 Divided City, Divided Heaven? Berlin Border Crossings in Post-Wende Fiction -- tCHAPTER 17 Interview with Barbara Hoidn -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex of Proper Names: People, Places, and Institutions0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA great deal of attention continues to focus on Berlin’s cultural and political landscape after the fall of the Berlin Wall, but as yet, no single volume looks at the divided city through an interdisciplinary analysis. This volume examines how the city was conceived, perceived, and represented during the four decades preceding reunification and thereby offers a unique perspective on divided Berlin’s identities. German historians, art historians, architectural historians, and literary and cultural studies scholars explore the divisions and antagonisms that defined East and West Berlin; and by tracing the little studied similarities and extensive exchanges that occurred despite the presence of the Berlin Wall, they present an indispensible study on the politics and culture of the Cold War.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh1 aBach, Ulrich, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarclay, David E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnstone, Deborah Ascher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBroadbent, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBroadbent, Philip, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat